  "response_text": "Tides are primarily caused by the gravitational forces exerted by the Moon and, to a lesser extent, the Sun on the Earth's oceans. Here\u2019s a more detailed explanation:\n\n1. **Gravitational Force**: The Moon is much closer to Earth than the Sun, so its gravitational pull is stronger. This gravitational force creates a tidal bulge on the side of Earth facing the Moon and another on the opposite side. The Sun also exerts a gravitational force, but because it is much farther away, its effect is about half as strong as that of the Moon.\n\n2. **Earth's Rotation**: As the Earth rotates, different parts of the planet experience these tidal bulges, resulting in the rise and fall of sea levels at various points around the globe. This rotation causes two high tides and two low tides each day in most locations.\n\n3. **Shape of the Ocean Basins**: The shape of the ocean basins can also affect the height and timing of tides.",
